{{coords|52.4501|N|9.0646|W|type:landmark_region:IE_LK|display=title}}
'''Ballygowan''' is an Irish brand of [[mineral water]]. It is bottled at [[Newcastle West]] in [[County Limerick]], near its [[Inflow (hydrology)|source]] at the site of a reputed [[holy well]] used by the [[Knights Templar]]. Ballygowan is the leading water brand in the Irish market, its name often used as a [[generic trademark]]. 

The company was founded by Geoff Read in 1981, who launched a marketing and distribution [[joint venture]] in 1984 with [[Nash (drinks)|Nash]], a [[soft drink]] manufacturer. [[Anheuser-Busch]] took a stake in 1987, which was bought back in 1989. In 1993, Ballygowan was bought by [[Cantrell and Cochrane]] (now C&C), which sold its non-alcoholic brands to [[Britvic]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/may/14/6|title=Britvic buys Ballygowan bottled water brand|last=Walsh|first=Fiona|date=14 May 2007|work=The Guardian|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> The 1993 deal involved Nash selling the source but retaining part of the source area, which it later used for its own rival spring water brand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/nash-continues-to-sparkle-1.1116367|title=Nash continues to sparkle|date=17 November 2000|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref> In 2014 Britvic discontinued its Drench and [[Pennine Spring]] water brands in Britain in favour of Ballygowan.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/will-ballygowan-water-brand-be-a-splash-hit-for-britvic/354297.article|title=Will Ballygowan water brand be a splash hit for Britvic?|last=Bamford|first=Vince|date=9 February 2014|journal=[[The Grocer]]|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-22626993|title=Britvic to close Chelmsford factory and put hundreds out of work|date=22 May 2013|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref>

