{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox lake | name = Lake Ouiachic | image = Ouiachic.jpg | caption = from space, October 1994 | image_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[Sierra Madre Occidental]], [[Cajeme]], [[Sonora]], [[Mexico]] | coords = {{Coord|27|53|N|109|55|W|region:MX_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}} | type = [[reservoir]] | inflow = [[Yaqui River]] | outflow = [[Yaqui River]] | catchment = | basin_countries = Mexico | length = | width = | area = | depth = | max-depth = | volume = | residence_time = | shore = | elevation = | islands = | cities = | frozen = }} '''Lake Ouiachic''' (also referred to as the '''Álvaro Obregón Reservoir''') is located in the foothills of the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]] and is created by the [[Álvaro Obregón Dam]]. Lake Ouiachic is fed by and drained by the [[Yaqui River]]. The dam was completed in 1952 with the purpose to regulate water flow of the Yaqui River, prevent floods, and generate electricity. Lake Ouiachic is also an expanding tourist and resort area specializing in [[fishing]], [[boating]], and [[water skiing]].
